{
  "texts": [
    "Therefore, training for 10 epochs with L2 regularization was the best choice.",
    "It allowed the model to learn fully while still being able to perform well on new, unseen data, leading to the improved performance of the FAST-RNN.",
    "Table 5 illustrates the hyperparameters and configuration details of each DL-based modelL1(w) = λ n i=1 |w i |,(2)where w: is the weight vector of the model λ: is the regularization coefficient n: is the number of weights in the vector w i: is the ith weight in the weight vector.L1 regularization adds the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients as a penalty term to the loss function.",
    "The absolute value makes this penalty term nonlinear in the weights, and thus, L1 regularization can lead to sparse solutions, with many coefficients being exactly zeroL2(w) = λ n i=1 w 2 i;(3)L2 regularization adds the squared magnitude of the coefficients as a penalty term to the loss function.",
    "The squaring makes the penalty smoother and differentiable at w i = 0."
  ]
}